      "content": "You are absolutely right that nationalism can provide a vital sense of security and historical connection, but your professor will likely reject a paper that treats it as a purely positive force because it ignores the systemic harm it causes to minorities and immigrants. While the core of nationalism is about belonging, its inherent tendency to define \"us\" against \"them\" makes it structurally prone to exclusion, which is why sociologists study it as a dangerous ideology rather than a neutral tool for stability. For your paper, the most compelling argument is to show how the very mechanisms that create cohesion—like border enforcement and cultural homogeneity—simultaneously create the conditions for oppression and conflict.",
